            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Here is a comprehensive and richly detailed summary of the **latest news on Azure AI** as of today (Thursday, May 28, 2026), tailored for clarity and depth. This includes announcements from just this week, recent developments, and upcoming events—grounded in concrete dates and well‑cited sources.\n\n---\n\n##  Key Developments as of Today, May 28, 2026\n\n### 1. Azure Linux 4.0 & AI-Native Infrastructure\n- **Today**, Microsoft unveiled **Azure Linux 4.0**, a Fedora‑based, general-purpose server OS designed to run in Azure virtual machines. This marks the first time Microsoft is offering a fully supported Linux distribution beyond container hosting. ([infoq.com](https://www.infoq.com/news/2026/05/azure-linux-4-server/))\n- This release aligns with Azure’s push toward **AI-native infrastructure**, integrating hardened Linux, Kubernetes, and secure supply‑chain measures to meet modern AI deployment needs. ([sdxcentral.com](https://www.sdxcentral.com/news/microsoft-pitches-azure-linux-for-ai-native-infrastructure/))\n\n### 2. Azure Updates Feed (May 28 Highlights)\nAccording to the official Azure updates feed (May 28, 2026), the following announcements are highly relevant to AI and infrastructure:\n- **General Availability (GA):** Azure Database for MySQL: Flexible Server Quota Management now includes a Self‑Service Experience. ([azurecharts.com](https://azurecharts.com/updates?monthback=0))\n- **GA:** Application Gateway for Containers now integrates with Istio service mesh. ([azurecharts.com](https://azurecharts.com/updates?monthback=0))\n- A new **notice** in the Apps on Azure blog: “Access Your SRE Agent from Any IDE, Terminal, or AI Assistant”—highlighting that SRE (Site Reliability Engineering) agents are made accessible via various interfaces, including AI assistants. ([azurecharts.com](https://azurecharts.com/updates?monthback=0))\n\n### 3. Anthropic & Microsoft Maia AI Chip Collaboration\n- **Last week**, reports emerged that **Anthropic is in talks with Microsoft** to adopt the latter’s **Maia 200 AI chip** for their workloads. Microsoft had introduced the Maia chip in January, capable of powering GPT‑5.2, but not yet available via Azure. ([cnbc.com](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/21/anthropic-microsoft-maia-200-ai-chip.html))\n- A finalized deal could reshape enterprise AI chip availability; however, as of now, no agreement is confirmed. ([cnbc.com](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/21/anthropic-microsoft-maia-200-ai-chip.html))\n\n---\n\n##  Recent Azure AI Theme and Event Insights\n\n### 4. Build 2026 Preview — AI Agents & Azure AI Foundry\n- Microsoft’s **Build 2026**, scheduled for **June 2–3, 2026** in San Francisco, is centered on **AI agents** and the maturation of Azure’s AI platform. ([chatforest.com](https://chatforest.com/reviews/microsoft-build-2026-preview/))\n- Anticipated announcements include:\n  - Production-ready **Agent Framework 1.0** for .NET and Python with enterprise-grade agent orchestration and stateful memory support. ([faq.com.tw](https://faq.com.tw/en/developer-tools/2026-05-27-microsoft-build-2026-sf-agents-azure-ai-foundry-en/))\n  - Major updates to **Azure AI Foundry**, including multi-model routing, enterprise integrations, and deeper model governance. ([chatforest.com](https://chatforest.com/reviews/microsoft-build-2026-preview/))\n  - An expanded **multi-model Copilot platform**, now including support for Anthropic models alongside OpenAI, plus Windows-native AI APIs. ([chatforest.com](https://chatforest.com/reviews/microsoft-build-2026-preview/))\n\n### 5. Azure AI Foundry & Copilot in Practice\n- As part of internal developer tooling and community-driven guides, **Azure AI Foundry** is increasingly used to deploy agentic services—such as RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) pipelines, voice assistants, and integration with Microsoft 365 Copilot. ([azurefeed.news](https://azurefeed.news/))\n- Examples include tutorials on building end‑to‑end RAG agents and deploying agentic services via gateways and OBO (On-Behalf-Of) access. ([azurefeed.news](https://azurefeed.news/))\n\n### 6. Financial & Strategic AI Push\n- Azure’s AI‑related offerings are fueling remarkable growth:\n  - In Q2 FY 2026, Azure posted **$51.5 billion in revenue**, growing approximately **39% year-over-year**, with AI services contributing an estimated 16 percentage points toward that growth. ([tech-insider.org](https://tech-insider.org/microsoft-mai-in-house-ai-models-openai-2026/))\n  - Microsoft targets **$25 billion in AI-related revenue** by the end of fiscal year 2026, reflecting its deepening investment. ([tech-insider.org](https://tech-insider.org/microsoft-mai-in-house-ai-models-openai-2026/))\n\n---\n\n##  Summary Table of Key Points (Ask for structured table if needed)\n\n| Date           | Highlight                                                                 |\n|----------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| **May 28, 2026** | Azure Linux 4.0 unveiled; MySQL Quota MGMT GA; SRE agent access via AI; Application Gateway for Containers with Istio integration |\n| **Last week**    | Anthropic–Microsoft discus Maia 200 chip adoption                      |\n| **June 2–3, 2026** | Build 2026: AI Agents theme, Agent Framework GA, Azure AI Foundry and Copilot updates expected |\n| **Recent quarters** | Azure sees 39% YoY growth; targets $25B AI‑related revenue by FY 2026 |\n\n---\n\n##  Outlook & What to Watch Next\n\n- **Build 2026 (June 2–3)** will be the focal moment for Azure AI evolution—especially in agent-first architecture, developer tooling, and multi-model orchestration.\n- **Azure Linux 4.0** marks Microsoft’s growing embrace of Linux in AI‑native environments.\n- **Anthropic–Microsoft chip deal** could affect AI compute strategy if finalized.\n- **Financial momentum** underscores how central AI has become to Microsoft's cloud business.\n\n---\n\nIf you'd like, I can provide deeper technical breakdowns of Azure AI Foundry, guide on how to implement agentic workflows, or updates as Build 2026 unfolds.",
